    thinking: "**Refining the Description**\n\nI am currently working on refining the description for the ambient mixer. My aim is to elegantly convey that the background noise option is intentionally disabled. I need to emphasize its absence in favor of a clinical entrainment experience, aligning it perfectly with the user\'s desire for purity and ultra-clean results.\n\n\n**Revising UI Implementation**\n\nI\'m now revising the UI implementation for the background mixer. Rather than completely removing the option, I\'m leaning toward keeping it but disabling it by default with a \"Recommended Off\" badge. This approach allows users to override it if desired, while clearly communicating that the default state prioritizes a pure, tone-only experience for optimal results. Simplifying and cleaning up the notice is key to respecting user intent.\n\n\n**Optimizing UX Copy**\n\nI am now focusing on refining the UX copy. My goal is to clearly communicate the rationale behind disabling the background ambience while still offering options. The current text \"Desactivada por preferencia para sostener estimulaci\303\263n cl\303\255nica de tonos puros y evitar fatiga\" is a good start in Spanish, but I need to ensure a compelling translation. I also want to experiment with different labels for the options (Muto, Est\303\241tico, Tierra, C\303\263smico) to convey the intended sonic experience effectively.\n\n\n**Evaluating Visual States**\n\nI am currently evaluating visual states for the ambient mixer. Specifically, I am thinking through the nuances of the styling for the ambientType buttons and the slider associated with the ambient volume. The goal is a clear visual representation of the active/inactive state of both. I want the user to instantly grasp which ambient is selected and at what volume. My focus is on ensuring the inactive state is subtly distinct, while the active state is prominent.\n\n\n"
